1 Introduction

The data we analyzed consisting of the 20,000 websites using the technology of our main competitor Hotjar. Domain, Website Language, Global and Local Traffic Rank and Number of Referring Domains are the variables. The dataset is exported from hunter.io and enhanced by Alexa Rank tool of SEO Tools for Excel Add-on.

Hotjar is one of the strongest technology giving service in heatmaps and session recording to websites.

Here, you can see some visuals about Hotjar:

They provide service for almost 450,000 websites across the world. Some of the most leading countries provided after United States and United Kingdom are Brazil, Netherlands, Germany, and France.

The websites purchased Hotjar have verticals mostly like Computer Electronics&Technology, Business&Consumer Services, and Others which can be consisted of News&Media, Arts&Entertainment, E-commerce, etc.

Hotjar is also very popular among the sites having the most monthly visits around the world as Google, Taboola, or Mediafire.

2 Data Analyses

2.1 Alexa Ranking of Websites

When we group the 20k websites using Hotjar by their Alexa rankings. Alexa rankings which show traffic levels are categorized as:

Very High -> Lower than 5000

High -> Between 5000 and 100000

Medium -> Between 100000 and 250000

Low -> Between 250000 and 500000

Very Low -> Higher than 500000

Since our sample data contains the websites which are in a very large interval of 294-33,474,711 Alexa Global Rank, and total number of elements are only 20K; most of the websites stay as outliers.

With the help of this chart, we can deduce that rather than websites having only high traffic levels, domains having least monthly visits and almost non-traffic at all are also eager to demand this kind of service. They prefer Hotjar more than we guess to enhance their UX and increase their traffic and clicks. However, it looks like majority gains no benefit still.

2.2 Referring Domains

When we examine the total number of referring domains in each traffic level group, we observe some deviation due to the reason I have mentioned in the previous chart: missing information. Ideally, it would be expected that the amount of referring domains/backlinks is higher as traffic level gets high.

Since there are lots of domains having very low traffic, total number of referring links of that category deviated the chart. However, not much as we see by High Traffic Level is still on position 2.

2.3 Language of Websites

When we group the 20k websites using Hotjar by the language used, and when we exclude English to prevent the deviation, we observe that French, Spanish, Dutch, Portuguese and German are used in most of them.
